---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

export const meta = {
  title: 'Email Etiquette Guide',
  description: 'Professional email etiquette guide covering subject lines, greetings, body structure, signatures, CC vs BCC, reply all rules, tone, and common mistakes.',
  category: 'list',
  published: '2026-03-24'
};

const SITE_ID = 'papyruspeople';

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article"
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "When should I use CC vs BCC?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Use CC when you want to keep someone in the loop who isn't the primary recipient. Use BCC when you want to send an email to a large group without exposing everyone's email addresses or when removing someone from a thread to spare their inbox."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best way to start a professional email?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "'Dear [Name]' is best for formal or initial contact. 'Hi [Name]' is the standard for most professional correspondence. 'Hey [Name]' should be reserved for close colleagues or very casual workplaces."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How long should I wait before sending a follow-up email?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For general inquiries, wait 2-3 business days. For job applications, wait a week to 10 days. If the matter is urgent, 24 hours is acceptable."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "When should I call instead of sending an email?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Call when the topic is sensitive, highly complex, requires immediate back-and-forth discussion, or if the email thread has become too long and confusing."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What makes a good email signature?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A good signature is concise (3-4 lines). It should include your name, title, company, and phone number. Avoid large images, long quotes, or excessive links."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---

<SiteLayout
  site={SITE_ID}
  title={meta.title}
  description={meta.description}
  schema={JSON.stringify(schema)}
  canonical="https://papyruspeople.photonbuilder.com/email-etiquette-guide"
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Professional Email Etiquette Guide</h1>
      <p>Master the art of professional communication with our comprehensive guide to writing effective, polite, and impactful emails.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Subject Line Formulas</h2>
      <p>A strong subject line determines whether your email gets opened. Keep it brief and descriptive.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Action Required:</strong> [Action Required] Review Q3 Report by Friday</li>
        <li><strong>Question:</strong> Quick question regarding the upcoming campaign</li>
        <li><strong>Introduction:</strong> Introduction: [Your Name] / [Company]</li>
        <li><strong>Update:</strong> Status Update: Project Apollo</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Greeting Etiquette (Dear vs Hi vs Hey)</h2>
      <p>Your greeting sets the tone for the entire email. Choose wisely based on your relationship with the recipient.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Dear [Name]:</strong> Formal, traditional, best for initial outreach or conservative industries.</li>
        <li><strong>Hi [Name]:</strong> The modern standard. Professional yet approachable.</li>
        <li><strong>Hey [Name]:</strong> Casual. Use only with colleagues you know well or in very relaxed cultures.</li>
        <li><strong>To Whom It May Concern:</strong> Avoid if possible. Try to find a specific name or use a functional title (e.g., "Dear Hiring Manager").</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Body Structure & Length Best Practices</h2>
      <p>Emails should be easy to skim and clearly state their purpose.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The BLUF Method:</strong> Bottom Line Up Front. State your purpose in the first sentence.</li>
        <li><strong>Formatting:</strong> Use bullet points and short paragraphs to break up text.</li>
        <li><strong>Length:</strong> Keep emails short. If it takes more than three paragraphs, consider a phone call or meeting.</li>
        <li><strong>One Topic:</strong> Stick to one main topic per email to avoid confusion.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>CC vs BCC Rules & Reply All</h2>
      <p>Misusing these features is a quick way to annoy your colleagues.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>CC (Carbon Copy):</strong> Use to keep someone informed, but no action is required from them.</li>
        <li><strong>BCC (Blind Carbon Copy):</strong> Use for mass emails to protect privacy, or when moving someone to BCC to spare them from a long thread.</li>
        <li><strong>Reply All:</strong> Use sparingly. Only use when everyone on the thread truly needs to see your response.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Email Tone (Formal vs Casual)</h2>
      <p>Matching the recipient's tone is key to effective communication.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Formal:</strong> Use full sentences, proper grammar, avoid slang/emojis. Best for clients or superiors.</li>
        <li><strong>Casual:</strong> More conversational, acceptable to use exclamation points sparingly. Best for close teammates.</li>
        <li><strong>Rule of Thumb:</strong> Mirror the tone of the person you are emailing. If they are formal, you should be formal.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Cold Email Templates & Follow-ups</h2>
      <p>Reaching out to someone you don't know requires a specific approach.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The Hook:</strong> Start with something relevant to them (e.g., "I enjoyed your recent article...").</li>
        <li><strong>The Value:</strong> Briefly explain what you offer and why they should care.</li>
        <li><strong>The Call to Action (CTA):</strong> Make it easy for them to say yes (e.g., "Are you open to a 10-minute chat next week?").</li>
        <li><strong>Follow-up Timing:</strong> Wait 3-5 days before sending a polite bump. Limit to 2-3 follow-ups total.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Apology Emails & Common Mistakes</h2>
      <p>Mistakes happen. Knowing how to apologize professionally is crucial.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Own It:</strong> Apologize clearly and directly. Don't make excuses.</li>
        <li><strong>Offer a Solution:</strong> Explain what you are doing to fix the issue or prevent it in the future.</li>
        <li><strong>Common Mistakes:</strong> Spelling errors (especially names!), forgetting attachments, or sending to the wrong person. Always double-check before hitting send.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Out-of-Office (OOO) Messages</h2>
      <p>A good OOO message manages expectations while you are away.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Dates:</strong> Clearly state the exact dates you are unavailable.</li>
        <li><strong>Response Time:</strong> Indicate when they can expect a reply.</li>
        <li><strong>Alternative Contact:</strong> Provide the name and email of someone they can contact in an emergency.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Email Sign-offs Ranked</h2>
      <p>How you close your email leaves a lasting impression.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Best / Best regards:</strong> Universally acceptable, safe choice.</li>
        <li><strong>Sincerely:</strong> Formal, slightly outdated but still used in cover letters.</li>
        <li><strong>Thanks / Many thanks:</strong> Good for when you are asking for a favor or action.</li>
        <li><strong>Cheers:</strong> Casual, common in the UK/Australia, use with caution in formal US settings.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Email vs Call vs Slack</h2>
      <p>Choosing the right medium is half the battle.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Email:</strong> For formal communication, documentation, detailed updates, and external contacts.</li>
        <li><strong>Slack/Teams:</strong> For quick questions, team banter, and informal collaboration.</li>
        <li><strong>Call/Meeting:</strong> For complex topics, sensitive issues, brainstorming, or when a thread goes past three replies.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      {schema[1].mainEntity.map((faq: any) => (
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>{faq.name}</h3>
          <p>{faq.acceptedAnswer.text}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

  <style>
    .page-content { max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; margin-bottom: 2.5rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }

    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color, #2a2418); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; }

    .content-section { margin-top: 2rem; }
    .content-section h2 { font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .content-section h3 { font-size: 1.15rem; font-weight: 600; margin-top: 1.25rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .content-section p { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
    ul { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
    li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }

    .faq-item { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color, #2a2418); padding-bottom: 1.25rem; margin-bottom: 1.25rem; }
    .faq-item:last-child { border-bottom: none; margin-bottom: 0; padding-bottom: 0; }
    .faq-item h3 { margin-top: 0; }
  </style>

  <div class="related-tools" style="margin-top:3rem;padding-top:2rem;border-top:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);">
    <h2 style="font-size:1.2rem;margin-bottom:1rem;">🔗 Related Tools</h2>
    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(280px,1fr));gap:1rem;">
      <a href="/punctuation-guide" style="display:block;background:rgba(255,255,255,0.03);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);border-radius:10px;padding:1.25rem;text-decoration:none;color:inherit;transition:border-color 0.2s,transform 0.2s;" onmouseover="this.style.borderColor='rgba(255,255,255,0.2)';this.style.transform='translateY(-2px)'" onmouseout="this.style.borderColor='rgba(255,255,255,0.08)';this.style.transform='none'">
        <strong style="font-size:0.95rem;">Complete Punctuation Guide: Rules & Uses</strong>
        <p style="opacity:0.6;font-size:0.83rem;margin:0.4rem 0 0;line-height:1.4;">Punctuation reference covering commas, semicolons, colons, dashes, apostrophes, quotation marks, parentheses, and more. ...</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>
